You may do whatever you want with the Battlify source code and other source
files (from here on referred to as the "Battlify Source"), with the following
restrictions:

- If you publish any work derived from the Battlify Source, you must make it
  apparent in some way that it is derived from the Battlify Source.
- If you have created an executable program (from here on called "Your Program")
  compiled from some source code and/or other source files (from here on called
  "Your Source"), and if Your Source includes files or source code copied or
  derived from the Battlify Source, then you may only publish Your Program under
  the following conditions:
    - Your Program does not contain any malware or hidden malicious content.
    - You may not charge users money for Your Program, and Your Source must
      contain the monetization systems, including the licensing, trial-period
      tracking, and payment system, present in the Battlify Source without any
      alterations, and all of these systems must be active and working as
      intended in Your Program. That is unless Your Source features substantial
      improvements or additions to the Battlify Source, such that Your Source
      should be considered its own, derivative work, separate from the Battlify
      Source.

