# Notes on the Battlify License

The Battlify License is based on the MIT and DBAD licenses. It is designed with
two goals:

1. To prevent people with malicious intent — or who are just trying to make a
   quick buck — from publishing apps based on Battlify. For example, an app that
   looks like Battlify but contains malware, or an app that is identical to
   Battlify except that someone other than the original author gets paid when you
   buy a license.
2. To allow everyone else who doesn't have malicious intent to do whatever they
   like with the source code — including reusing it in their own free or
   monetized projects, or writing bug fixes and improvements and publishing them.
   It also allows someone to make a substantial improvement to Battlify and to
   charge for that improved version, or release it for free.

The intent is to be Open Source in spirit, with some protection against bad
actors now that Battlify is monetized. There are no restrictions on how you use
the source code — only on publishing apps compiled from it.

This license is provided as-is and is not legal advice; consult a lawyer before
relying on it commercially.
